This approach:

1. Uses Django's cache backend to track number of running instances
2. Implements a semaphore-like mechanism using atomic increment/decrement operations
3. Will retry the task if it can't acquire the lock
4. Properly cleans up the counter when task completes or fails
5. Has a timeout to prevent infinite waiting
6. Is thread-safe and works across multiple workers

You can customize:
- `max_concurrency`: Maximum number of concurrent tasks
- `lock_expire`: How long to keep track of running tasks
- Retry behavior when lock can't be acquired

Make sure your cache backend (Redis recommended) is properly configured in Django settings.
